Show HN: Turn your Git repository into a shareable VS Code sandbox
text:
Hi HN, I'm Edouard, founder of Kadabra (https://kadabra.dev). We're building a tool that can convert a Git repository into a Visual Studio Code sandbox.

We've spoken to a number of Python project owners and all have voiced the same thing. They want to make it easy for prospective users to evaluate their offering.

Running a pip install locally is frowned upon by security-wary users. Most projects therefore resort to using Google Colab for demo purposes, which comes with many flaws:

- Colab is still stuck on Python 3.7, which was first released in June 2018. - You don't have control over the development environment, so demo notebooks often start with long-drawn-out pip install. - There's no easy way to programmatically create a notebook. If you want to create one notebook per prospect with different API keys, it's not possible. - By nature, notebooks often constrain demos to running a series of Shift+Enter, which isn't the most endowing for a user that wants to first see what your package is all about. - Jupyter still suffers from limitations around code autocompletion and code navigation.

We wanted to address all these issues with Kadabra and enable project owners to create engaging onboarding experience for their users. Check out our progress with an example here: https://www.app.kadabra.dev/r/od0pdgu135gh9wj8/

If you're interested in using it for your git repo, feel free to shoot us an email at hello@kadabra.dev or sign-up for the private beta here: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfmQp2O7glexfn_owjc...

Show HN: Emery – Personal Planner
text:
We're building an app that helps people organize their days and weeks. In a nutshell, it's a workspace that combines tasks, notes, and calendar events.

Emery users can see their days and weeks on a single screen, manage their personal and professional tasks, access a single schedule of all their calendars, and navigate through their days without switching between multiple apps.

What we've built so far:

- A web app for desktop (standalone is coming soon) - Bi-directional Google calendar integration (including multiple accounts) - Daily and weekly planning screens with extensive usage of drag'n'drop - Time blocking for tasks - Different types of tasks – daily, weekly, "until done" - Basic note-taking functionality

Also, Emery has some things we always wanted to see in other apps – private notes for meetings, group editing of overdue tasks, categories to group tasks/notes/meetings together, and weekly productivity reports.

What's cooking:

- Recurring tasks - Standalone desktop app (trying Tauri)

Coming later:

- Outlook integration - Mobile apps

Happy to hear any feedback and answer any questions!
